Claims Claims 1. A method for constructing a solid-state reference electrode for use in an analyte-selective intracutaneously- or subcutaneously-implanted electrochemical cell, said method comprising: immersing a metallic electrode in a solution comprising a monomer precursor; applying a fixed or time-varying electrical potential or current to the metallic electrode, thereby serving to simultaneously electro-polymerize the monomer precursor and electro-deposit a conducting polymer, synthesized from the electro-polymerization of said monomer precursor, onto the said metallic electrode surface. 2. The method of claim 1, wherein metallic electrode includes chromium, titanium, tin, nickel, copper, silver, gold, platinum, palladium, rhodium, and iridium. 3. The method of claim 1, wherein said conducting polymer includes at least one of poly(aniline), poly(acetylene), poly(phenylene), poly(phenylenediaminie), poly(phenylene-vinylene), poly(phenylene-sulfide), poly(pyrrole), poly(thiophene), and poly(3,4-ethylenedioxythiophene). 4. The method of claim 1, wherein said monomer precursor includes at least one of aniline, acetylene, phenylene, phenylenediamine, phenylene-vinylene, phenylene- sulfide, pyrrole, thiophene, and 3,4-ethylenedioxythiophene. 5. The method of claim 3, further comprising forming two or more layers of the conducting polymer. 6. The method of claim 1, wherein said solution contains a counter anion or cation to serve as the charge carrier or dopant within the conducting polymer. The method of claim 5, wherein said counter anion includes chloride, sulfate, phosphate, and nitrate. 8. The method of claim 5, wherein said counter cation includes hydrogen, lithium, sodium, potassium, calcium, and magnesium. 9. The method of claim 1, wherein said fixed or time-varying electrical potential or current is applied using one of amperometry, voltammetry, and coulometry. 10. The method of claim 1, wherein said fixed or time-varying electrical potential or current is applied to encourage the formation of a radical anion or cation, thereby yielding charge carriers within the electro-deposited conducting polymer. 11. The method of claim 1, wherein said fixed or time-varying electrical potential or current is applied to reduce or oxidize the monomer precursor, thereby giving rise to charge carriers within the electro-deposited conducting polymer. 12. An analyte- selective intracutaneously- or subcutaneously-implanted electrochemical cell device, said device comprising: a contingent of one or multiple metallic electrodes; and a layer of electro-deposited conducting polymer on said metallic electrode contingent to form a solid-state reference electrode with a stable electrode potential; wherein said electrochemical cell device refers electrochemical measurements at a working electrode against said solid-state reference electrode. 13. The device of claim 11, wherein metallic electrode includes chromium, titanium, tin, nickel, copper, silver, gold, platinum, palladium, rhodium, and iridium. 14. The device of claim 11, wherein said conducting polymer comprises at least one of poly(aniline), poly(acetylene), poly(phenylene), poly(phenylene-vinylene), poly(phenylene-sulfide), poly(pyrrole), poly(thiophene), and poly(3,4- ethy 1 enedi oxy thi ophene) . 15. The device of claim 11, wherein said conducting polymer contains a counter anion or cation to serve as the charge carrier or dopant. 16. The device of claim 14, wherein said counter anion includes chloride, sulfate, phosphate, and nitrate. 17. The device of claim 14, wherein said counter cation includes hydrogen, lithium, sodium, potassium, calcium, and magnesium. 18. A method for constructing a solid-state reference electrode, the method comprising: immersing a metallic electrode in a solution comprising a monomer precursor; applying a fixed electrical potential to the metallic electrode, to simultaneously electro-polymerize the monomer precursor and electro-deposit a conducting polymer onto a surface of the metallic electrode to form a solid state reference electrode, wherein the conducting polymer is synthesized from the electro- polymerization of the monomer precursor. 19. The method according to claim 18 wherein the metallic electrode is composed of one of chromium, titanium, tin, nickel, copper, silver, gold, platinum, palladium, rhodium, and iridium. 20. The method according to claim 18 wherein the conducting polymer includes at least one of poly(aniline), poly(acetylene), poly(phenylene), poly(phenylenediaminie), poly(phenylene-vinylene), poly(phenylene-sulfide), poly(pyrrole), poly(thiophene), and poly(3,4-ethylenedioxythiophene). 21. The method according to claim 18 wherein the monomer precursor includes at least one of aniline, acetylene, phenylene, phenylenediamine, phenylene-vinylene, phenylene-sulfide, pyrrole, thiophene, and 3,4-ethylenedioxythiophene. 22. The method according to claim 20 further comprising forming two or more layers of the conducting polymer. 23. The method according to claim 18 wherein the solution comprises a counter anion or a counter cation as a charge carrier or dopant within the conducting polymer. 24. The method according to claim 23 wherein the counter anion is one of chloride, sulfate, phosphate, and nitrate. 25. The method according to claim 23 wherein the counter cation is one of hydrogen, lithium, sodium, potassium, calcium, and magnesium. 26. The method according to claim 18 wherein the fixed electrical potential is applied using one of amperometry, voltammetry, and coulometry. 27. The method according to claim 18 wherein the fixed electrical potential is applied to encourage the formation of a radical anion or cation, to yield charge carriers within the electro-deposited conducting polymer. 28. The method according to claim 18 wherein the fixed electrical potential is applied to reduce or oxidize the monomer precursor, to generate charge carriers within the electro-deposited conducting polymer. 29. A met